description.value: Fragment of an ostracon from a pottery vessel, showing four lines of hieratic text written in black ink at the outside, parallel to the rim but in quite thick writing.  The sherd is part of a plate or bowl with a red rim at the inside and edge, probably 20cm in diameter. The object shows a fresh break and might therefore join other fragments. The vessel was made of Nile clay with chaff and mica inclusions, it was wheel made and shows white and black accretions at the inside and possible salt at the outside.

description.value: Fragment of an ostracon from a pottery vessel consisting of two joined sherds. The outside was well smoothed and shows remains of black and red ink, remains of two columnsof signs identifiable with red colour underneath the black one.  Two modern lines in black indicate the joint on the inside.  The sherd was part of an imported vessel, probably an amphora as it shows a cream slip on the outside and lots of lime in the break. On the inside remains of a whitish substance that might be traces of the original content.

description.value: Limestone ostracon: the verso shows a lion's head sketched in black ink in profile; the space around it has been filled with less impressive attempts to draw a fledgling. Since this was a hieroglyphic sign used to write the word 'tja', "fledgling," and other words containing the same sound, its shape had to be exactly right, from the open beak with tongue extended and the featherless little wings to the huge three-clawed foot and the tiny curl of a tail. The largest example, though not as well drawn as the lion head, looks like professional work. The corrections are made in red ink. The recto shows a throne.
